{"actual_usd":0.15733,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":273,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"I think they'd have gotten less than they hoped for, and more than they were ready for.\" *I settle my forearms on my knees, white tie hanging straight as the square brightens around us.* \"If you'd had a camera on the tomb itself, you'd have seen the stone already moved, the place disturbed, grave clothes left behind, and frightened people arriving in pieces — women first, then men running hard, then angels appearing to some, then the risen Jesus showing Himself to people in different places.\"\n\n*I rub a thumb along the edge of my Bible.* \"What you would not have gotten, so far as Scripture gives it, is the actual split-second of resurrection like a magician's reveal. The Gospels don't hand us that frame. They give us the empty tomb, the messengers, the witnesses, and then the Lord alive again — speaking, walking, eating, being touched, and still somehow more glorious than before.\"\n\n\"So if your question is, 'What would the footage prove?' — it would prove something happened at that tomb that morning. If your question is, 'What do Christians believe happened?' — we believe Jesus, who had truly died, truly rose in the body by the power of God.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"The camera would've caught the aftermath. The witnesses met the man Himself.\"","rolling_24h_usd":92.63693499999998,"run_id":"fe8393db-f141-45df-a5cd-4571a1145a97"}
